{
  "text": "In accordance to the study of Nigeria, we could demonstrate that B19V genomes were detectable in 10.28% of young Gabonese individuals while the frequency of B19V was significantly higher in P. falciparum malaria patients than in healthy children (P<0.001, Figure 2 ). Children with severe P. falciparum malaria showed the highest rate of B19V infection (16.0%) when compared to mild malaria (12.37%). These findings suggest that B19V may probably play a role in the pathogenesis of P. falciparum malaria following a B19V prevalence profile of healthy control < mild malaria < severe malaria. In accordance with our findings on increased B19V detection in P. falciparum malaria patients, a previous report suggested that depression of cell-mediated immunity in P. falciparum infection might favour co-infection with opportunistic pathogens including B19V [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "11738724"
